"Alvear V.J.V.; León A.P.O.; Root M.S.","Alvear, Vanessa Janett Vélez (57208397126); León, Andrea Paulina Ordóñez (57215586839); Root, Maria Salas (58652575600)","57208397126; 57215586839; 58652575600","Urban sustainability in the Latin American intermediate city. The case of Loja - Ecuador; [Sustentabilidad urbana en la ciudad intermedia latinoamericana. El caso de Loja - Ecuador]","2023","Bitacora Urbano Territorial","33","3","","","","1","10.15446/bitacora.v33n3.109577","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85174345191&doi=10.15446%2Fbitacora.v33n3.109577&partnerID=40&md5=a32eeb25c93969b1e42a82fb465717f7","Universidad Internacional del Ecuador, Ecuador; Ci Design Inc, United States","Alvear V.J.V., Universidad Internacional del Ecuador, Ecuador; León A.P.O., Universidad Internacional del Ecuador, Ecuador; Root M.S., Ci Design Inc, United States","The UN 2030 Agenda pursues sustainable development, inclusion, and in coherence with the environment. To achieve this, it is necessary to evaluate and improve the sustainability of the cities. This study evaluated urban sustainability in a pilot sector of the intermediate city of Loja (Ecuador). The used methodology was based on the System of Sustainable Urban Evaluation through urban densification indicators. To obtain occupancy indicators of use and occupancy, pedestrian accessibility, green spaces, and social interaction, data sources were gathered. The results revealed low index values when compared to the index values proposed: five indexes show optimum values in portions of the area of study while three indexes did not reach acceptable values. The Urban Densification Index value is lower compared to the referent index. The study indicates low sustainable index-values of urban development in the pilot sector analyzed. These results make evident the need to quantify sustainability indexes within the city as a base to define objectives that guide the city planning towards sustainability and urban equality. © 2023 Universidad Nacional de Colombia. All rights reserved.","evaluation; intermediate city; urban development; urban indicators; Urban sustainability","","","","Universidad Nacional de Colombia","01247913","","","","Spanish","Bitacora Urban. Territorial","Article","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85174345191"
"Quezada C.R.; Guajardo F.J.; Steiniger S.","Quezada, Carolina Rojas (35254568700); Guajardo, Felipe Jorquera (57369490400); Steiniger, Stefan (18038653900)","35254568700; 57369490400; 18038653900","WALKING ACCESS TO URBAN WETLANDS: AN OPPORTUNITY FOR RECREATION AND WELLBEING; [ACCEDER CAMINANDO A LOS HUMEDALES URBANOS UNA OPORTUNIDAD DE RECREACIÓN Y BIENESTAR]","2022","Urbano","25","46","","56","67","8","10.22320/07183607.2022.25.46.05","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85149118970&doi=10.22320%2F07183607.2022.25.46.05&partnerID=40&md5=aac7be9e37a41a26112fd44113c08202","Geografía en Sistemas de Información Geográfica, Cartografía y Teledetección Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Instituto de Estudios Urbanos y Territoriales, Chile; Asentamientos Humanos y Medio Ambiente Universidad de Concepción, Concepción, Chile; Ciencias Ambientales, Facultad de Ciencias Ambientales - Centro EULA, Chile; Ingeniería Geomática Pontificia Universidad Católica de Valparaíso, Valparaíso, Chile; Escuela de Ingeniería de la Construcción y Transportes - Centro de Desarrollo Urbano Sustentable CEDEUS, Santiago, Chile","Quezada C.R., Geografía en Sistemas de Información Geográfica, Cartografía y Teledetección Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile, Instituto de Estudios Urbanos y Territoriales, Chile; Guajardo F.J., Asentamientos Humanos y Medio Ambiente Universidad de Concepción, Concepción, Chile, Ciencias Ambientales, Facultad de Ciencias Ambientales - Centro EULA, Chile; Steiniger S., Ingeniería Geomática Pontificia Universidad Católica de Valparaíso, Valparaíso, Chile, Escuela de Ingeniería de la Construcción y Transportes - Centro de Desarrollo Urbano Sustentable CEDEUS, Santiago, Chile","Urban wetlands in Chilean cities are one of the urban ecosystems most affected by real estate developments. Despite their importance for recreation and biodiversity, they are constantly shrinking due to deficient urban planning processes. However, with the recent boom of green and sustainable cities, wetlands are being revalued through restoration projects and open urban parks, with natural value for the well-being of habitats and the urban population. In this sense, promoting accessibility through suitable infrastructure will contribute to improving the quality of life of inhabitants and the urban environment, specifically through the integration of blue-green infrastructure. Walkable access to a network of wetlands called “La Ruta del Agua” (“the water trail”) has been analyzed here, through a perception-based survey, looking to improve access to nature in cities. The urban wetlands assessed comprise five ecosystems located in different types of neighborhoods in the metropolitan area of Concepción, Chile. Although this is a local case study, it is relevant from a methodological perspective, given the existence of a large number of degraded urban wetlands in Latin America that are in danger of disappearing. The results show that wetlands are accessible by walking, but the fact that they are rarely visited, despite being close to residential areas, reveals a lack of integration as open green spaces, rich in biodiversity, and as places of recreation in the city of Concepción. The results of this study are valuable for the design of future “wetland parks”, one which must consider the ecosystem values, biodiversity, and recreation for people’s well-being. © 2022 Authors. All rights reserved.","accessibility; perception; urban wetlands; walkability; well-being","","","","Universidad del Bío Bío","07173997","","","","English","Urbano","Article","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access; Green Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85149118970"
"Lima J.P.; Machado M.H.","Lima, Josiane Palma (37005921300); Machado, Mariza Helena (57190608924)","37005921300; 57190608924","Walking accessibility for individuals with reduced mobility: A Brazilian case study","2019","Case Studies on Transport Policy","7","2","","269","279","29","10.1016/j.cstp.2019.02.007","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85062425547&doi=10.1016%2Fj.cstp.2019.02.007&partnerID=40&md5=caa631a43df1ec9ac01643ce8f166aa7","Federal University of Itajuba (UNIFEI), Industrial Engineering and Management Institute (IEPG), Ave. Bps 1303, Itajuba, 37500-903, MG, Brazil","Lima J.P., Federal University of Itajuba (UNIFEI), Industrial Engineering and Management Institute (IEPG), Ave. Bps 1303, Itajuba, 37500-903, MG, Brazil; Machado M.H., Federal University of Itajuba (UNIFEI), Industrial Engineering and Management Institute (IEPG), Ave. Bps 1303, Itajuba, 37500-903, MG, Brazil","The objective of this work is to evaluate the accessibility in public spaces from the perspective of the person with reduced mobility. Two methods of evaluation were used: the Analytic Hierarchy Process (AHP), to consider the multiple criteria that define a quantitative index of the pedestrian accessibility; and the Commented Paths Method (Méthode des Parcours Commentés) for a qualitative analysis of the practical subjective experience. In order to apply the methods and compare the results, a case study was carried out in the city of Itajubá, in the state of Minas Gerais, Brazil. The results of the application of the methods when compared to the on-site observation, demonstrated coherence with the actual situation. One method complemented the other by providing greater potential for interpretation of the phenomenon, especially by adding individual perceptions, increasing the study's validity. The research provides support for more inclusive public policies, including accessibility with a view for sustainable development and a special focus on social sustainability. 