"Adlakha D.; Parra D.C.","Adlakha, Deepti (55532047200); Parra, Diana C. (55760782500)","55532047200; 55760782500","Mind the gap: Gender differences in walkability, transportation and physical activity in urban India","2020","Journal of Transport and Health","18","","100875","","","66","10.1016/j.jth.2020.100875","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85084813570&doi=10.1016%2Fj.jth.2020.100875&partnerID=40&md5=ad497e481794363974f2f03b749901d2","School of Natural and Built Environment, Queen's University Belfast, United Kingdom; Program in Physical Therapy, Washington University in St. Louis, School of Medicine, St. Louis, MO, United States","Adlakha D., School of Natural and Built Environment, Queen's University Belfast, United Kingdom; Parra D.C., Program in Physical Therapy, Washington University in St. Louis, School of Medicine, St. Louis, MO, United States","Introduction: Insufficient physical activity (PA) is a key contributor for premature mortality in low- and middle-income countries (LMICs). Despite the well-documented health benefits of PA, few women achieve the recommended levels of PA. The global average of inactivity among women is higher at 31.7% compared to 23.4% for inactive men. The gender gap in PA participation is wider in India where estimates indicate that 44% women are insufficiently active, compared to 25% men. Methods: This cross-sectional study was conducted in the city of Chennai, India. Participants (N = 370) were recruited from 155 wards stratified by neighborhood walkability and socio-economic status. The adapted Neighborhood Environment Walkability Scale for India (NEWS-India) was used to assess built environment perceptions on density, land-use mix, street infrastructure, aesthetics, traffic and crime safety. Travel and leisure PA were recorded using the International Physical Activity Questionnaire-Long Form (IPAQ-LF). Study protocols were based on recommendations of the International Physical activity and the Environment Network (IPEN; www.ipenproject.org) and previously used in studies in Brazil, Colombia, and Nigeria. Results: A greater number of women reported achieving weekly PA levels from travel-related activities (n = 54, 16.0%) compared to men (n = 33, 9.8%). In contrast, a higher percentage of men (n = 75, 22.3%) met weekly PA recommendations during leisure-time compared to women (n = 54, 16.1%). Street connectivity (aOR = 3.2, CI = 1.3, 8.0) and land-use mix access (aOR = 3.7, CI = 1.4, 8.2) significantly increased odds of travel PA among women. Conclusions: Low engagement in leisure PA among women can be linked to prevailing socio-cultural norms that constrain women's mobility and hinder their participation in PA. Aspects of gender equity in transportation planning are closely linked with citywide indicators of liveability, sustainability and resilience in LMICs like India. Public health practitioners must address gender-specific barriers to increase PA among women through context-specific group exercise programs, peer support and guidance that emphasize the importance of PA. © 2020 Elsevier Ltd","Built environment; India; Low- and middle-income countries; Neighborhood walkability; Non-communicable diseases; Physical activity","","D. Adlakha; School of Natural and Built Environment David Keir Building, Queen's University Belfast, Belfast, 39-123 Stranmillis Road, BT9 5AG, United Kingdom; email: d.adlakha@qub.ac.uk","","Elsevier Ltd","22141405","","","","English","J. Transp. Health","Article","Final","All Open Access; Green Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85084813570"
"Valverde-Caballero L.S.; Mendoza-Salazar L.M.; Butron-Revilla C.L.; Suarez-Lopez E.; Aguilar-Ruiz J.S.","Valverde-Caballero, Liliana S (57285821700); Mendoza-Salazar, Luis M (59032945300); Butron-Revilla, Cinthya L (58853380200); Suarez-Lopez, Ernesto (58002914200); Aguilar-Ruiz, Jesus S (57194168052)","57285821700; 59032945300; 58853380200; 58002914200; 57194168052","Walkability index for world heritage cities in developing countries","2025","Environment and Planning B: Urban Analytics and City Science","52","1","","76","96","4","10.1177/23998083241250265","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85192171366&doi=10.1177%2F23998083241250265&partnerID=40&md5=0559846ebe57108bc20724c894f250ed","Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Peru; Pablo de Olavide University, Spain","Valverde-Caballero L.S., Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Peru; Mendoza-Salazar L.M., Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Peru; Butron-Revilla C.L., Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Peru; Suarez-Lopez E., Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Peru; Aguilar-Ruiz J.S., Pablo de Olavide University, Spain","Walkability principles are an important part in the planning process of cities that face urban problems such as gentrification, pollution, and decay of their built heritage. The proposed factors – connectivity, proximity, land use mix, and retail density – form a comprehensive framework for evaluating walkability that transcends the boundaries of historical cities. These factors, while initially identified within historical contexts, possess inherent qualities that render them universally adaptable to various urban landscapes. By leveraging these factors, urban planners gain insights into the intricate fabric of pedestrian experiences in cities. They serve as universal evaluative tools, applicable not only to historical cities but also to burgeoning metropolises and smaller urban centres. This work introduces a novel approach to assessing the Walkability Index for World Heritage Cities, utilizing a Multiple Criteria Spatial Decision Support System (GIS-MCDA) structured in four stages. The approached methodology is particularly valuable for governments and decision-makers in developing countries of the Global South, where limitations in data and available tools are common challenges. The insights gained from this study can guide the improvement of policies, enable more precise implementation of sustainable mobility infrastructure, and motivate the pursuit or maintenance of UNESCO World Heritage nominations. The case study focused on the Historical Centre of Arequipa, Peru, a city designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. The results of this study demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed approach in such contexts, owing to its specificity and the integration of both objective and subjective elements. © The Author(s) 2024.","geographic information system; land use; pedestrian; UNESCO; Walkability index; world heritage","Arequipa [Arequipa (DPR)]; Arequipa [Peru]; Peru; developing world; GIS; land use; pedestrian; walking; World Heritage Site","L.S. Valverde-Caballero; Universidad Nacional de San Agustin de Arequipa, Arequipa, Santa Catalina 117, 04000, Peru; email: lvalverdec@unsa.edu.pe","","SAGE Publications Ltd","23998083","","","","English","Environ. Plann.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85192171366"
"Arellana J.; Alvarez V.; Oviedo D.; Guzman L.A.","Arellana, Julián (55569221400); Alvarez, Vilma (57208336033); Oviedo, Daniel (56271857200); Guzman, Luis A. (55904900500)","55569221400; 57208336033; 56271857200; 55904900500","Walk this way: Pedestrian accessibility and equity in Barranquilla and Soledad, Colombia","2021","Research in Transportation Economics","86","","101024","","","56","10.1016/j.retrec.2020.101024","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85099624597&doi=10.1016%2Fj.retrec.2020.101024&partnerID=40&md5=97c71b1ac9723f38d6731527d72ca101","Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad Del Norte, Colombia; University College London, United Kingdom; Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad de los Andes, Colombia","Arellana J., Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad Del Norte, Colombia; Alvarez V., Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad Del Norte, Colombia; Oviedo D., University College London, United Kingdom; Guzman L.A., Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad de los Andes, Colombia","As a transport mode available to everyone and most abled-bodied urban residents, walking is, actually, the most equitable mode of transport. Walking brings several benefits to inhabitants among money savings and health improvement. Unfortunately, despite its benefits, walking is not a priority in the urban planning agenda of some cities, especially in the Global South. Walkability conditions in some areas of these cities are not particularly friendly for pedestrians, which discourage walking trips and promotes inequities across inhabitants. Evidence supporting inequalities in the provision of adequate conditions for the use of active transport in the Global South cities remain scarce. This paper aims to contribute to filling this gap by first proposing a framework to link pedestrian accessibility with walkability measures. Specifically, we use a macro-scale measure of pedestrian accessibility and a meso-scale measure of walkability to compare walking conditions on different zones in Barranquilla and Soledad, Colombia. After comparing both measures, we found that low-income zones have higher walkability indexes but present lower potential pedestrian accessibility. In contrast, the highest potential pedestrian accessibilities were located in high and medium-income zones, where people rely more on private transport modes. This imbalance regarding supply and demand conditions for walking trips suggest that unfortunately, zones with the highest potential of being walkable are the ones that face more barriers to walk. Then, adequate planning policies when implemented in the right locations could promote higher use of walking and have the potential to reduce current inequalities in pedestrian infrastructure provision. © 2021 Elsevier Ltd","Barranquilla; Equity; Pedestrians; Potential pedestrian accessibility; Soledad; Walkability index; Walking","","J. Arellana; Departamento de Ingeniería Civil y Ambiental, Universidad Del Norte, Colombia; email: jarellana@uninorte.edu.co","","Emerald Group Holdings Ltd.","07398859","","","","English","Res. Transp. Econ.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85099624597"
"Correa-Parra J.; Vergara-Perucich F.; Aguirre-Nuñez C.; Ulloa-León F.I.","Correa-Parra, Juan (59004361700); Vergara-Perucich, Francisco (57225924150); Aguirre-Nuñez, Carlos (57915892800); Ulloa-León, Felipe Ignacio (57790234500)","59004361700; 57225924150; 57915892800; 57790234500","The 15-minute city and real estate capital: contributions from Chile’s major cities","2025","Town Planning Review","96","6","","671","696","1","10.3828/tpr.2025.8","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105020747517&doi=10.3828%2Ftpr.2025.8&partnerID=40&md5=a92e0522d84d4f6a270390b5a23c8684","Universidad Gabriela Mistral, Escuela de Arquitectura, Avenida Andrés Bello 1337, Santiago Metropolitan Region, 7500533, Chile; Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile, Instituto de Geografía, Vicuña Mackenna 4860, Santiago Metropolitan, 7820436, Chile; Universidad de las Americas, Manuel Montt 948, Providencia, RM, Santiago, 7500972, Chile; Universidad San Sebastián – Campus Bellavista, Facultad de ingeniería, arquitectura y diseño, Bellavista 7, Recoleta, RM, Santiago de Chile, 8420524, Chile; Universidad de las Américas – Arquitectura, Manuel Montt 498, RM, Santiago, 7500975, Chile","Correa-Parra J., Universidad Gabriela Mistral, Escuela de Arquitectura, Avenida Andrés Bello 1337, Santiago Metropolitan Region, 7500533, Chile, Pontificia Universidad Catolica de Chile, Instituto de Geografía, Vicuña Mackenna 4860, Santiago Metropolitan, 7820436, Chile; Vergara-Perucich F., Universidad de las Americas, Manuel Montt 948, Providencia, RM, Santiago, 7500972, Chile; Aguirre-Nuñez C., Universidad San Sebastián – Campus Bellavista, Facultad de ingeniería, arquitectura y diseño, Bellavista 7, Recoleta, RM, Santiago de Chile, 8420524, Chile; Ulloa-León F.I., Universidad de las Américas – Arquitectura, Manuel Montt 498, RM, Santiago, 7500975, Chile","The COVID-19 pandemic has spurred discussions on reimagining cities based on principles of public health and reducing spatially expressed inequalities. In this context, the concept of the 15-minute city has emerged as a priority for municipal authorities in the case of Chile. However, the implementation of this model faces challenges, including the dominant presence of the market in the production and capitalisation of urban life in Chilean cities. © 2025 Liverpool University Press. All rights reserved.","15-minute city; real estate; urbanism; walkable city","Chile; capital; policy implementation; public health; urban planning","","","Liverpool University Press","00410020","","","","English","Town Plann. Rev.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-105020747517"
"da Silva M.B.C.; de Toni D.; Bertolini A.C.F.","da Silva, Marcelo Benetti Correa (57218372147); de Toni, Deonir (35785647800); Bertolini, Ana Cristina Fachinelli (59722837000)","57218372147; 35785647800; 59722837000","The influence of perceived dimensions of sustainability on life satisfaction and citizen engagement in developing countries","2026","Cities","172","","106842","","","0","10.1016/j.cities.2026.106842","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105030261062&doi=10.1016%2Fj.cities.2026.106842&partnerID=40&md5=17d69ab8019ac935cf425bc2a45af5a5","University of Caxias do Sul, Business and Social Sciences, Department of Business Administration, Brazil","da Silva M.B.C., University of Caxias do Sul, Business and Social Sciences, Department of Business Administration, Brazil; de Toni D., University of Caxias do Sul, Business and Social Sciences, Department of Business Administration, Brazil; Bertolini A.C.F., University of Caxias do Sul, Business and Social Sciences, Department of Business Administration, Brazil","This study examines how citizens' perceptions of key urban sustainability dimensions relate to their well-being and civic engagement. We focus on mid-sized industrial cities in southern Brazil, a context that remains underrepresented in the urban sustainability literature, to address a gap in Global South evidence. The analysis is based on a quantitative, cross-sectional survey applying the CityLifeSat scale to 1228 residents in two municipalities. Perceived sustainability was operationalized through multiple latent constructs aligned with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) and with indicators from ISO 37120:2017, including safety, recreation, walkability, mobility, primary services, place attachment, and health and well-being. We estimated a Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Model (PLS-SEM) to test the relationships among these constructs and civic engagement. The results show that citizens' perceptions of safety and place attachment are positively associated with civic engagement, indicating that feeling secure and emotionally connected to the city supports participation in local decision-making. Health and well-being are significantly and positively influenced by perceptions of safety, recreation, and primary services, demonstrating that everyday conditions—protection, access to services, and opportunities for leisure—are central to perceived urban sustainability. At the same time, lower levels of health and well-being are associated with higher levels of civic engagement, suggesting that dissatisfaction with urban conditions can motivate political participation and demands for accountability. These findings advance existing debates by empirically linking perceived sustainability, subjective well-being, and civic engagement in a Global South setting, and by showing that civic engagement is driven both by positive attachment and by dissatisfaction. The study contributes methodologically by validating the CityLifeSat model through PLS-SEM and confirming the reliability of most constructs derived from SDG- and ISO-based indicators. Practically, the results provide city managers with an evidence-based framework to prioritize investments in safety, essential services, and inclusive public spaces as levers to promote both well-being and participatory urban governance. Copyright © 2024. Published by Elsevier Ltd.","Citizen engagement; City life satisfaction; Sustainability","Brazil; developing world; life satisfaction; sustainability; urban development; urbanization","M.B.C. da Silva; Universidade de Caxias do Sul, Business Management, Caxias do Sul, 1130, Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Rio Grande do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil; email: mbcsilva@ucs.br","","Elsevier Ltd","02642751","","","","English","Cities","Article","Final","All Open Access; Hybrid Gold Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-105030261062"
"Duduta N.; Adriazola C.; Hidalgo D.; Lindau L.A.; Jaffe R.","Duduta, Nicolae (55616079000); Adriazola, Claudia (55256344900); Hidalgo, Dario (7006017161); Lindau, Luis Antonio (25122780900); Jaffe, Rebecca (56735508200)","55616079000; 55256344900; 7006017161; 25122780900; 56735508200","Understanding road safety impact of high-performance bus rapid transit and busway design features","2012","Transportation Research Record","2317","","","8","14","41","10.3141/2317-02","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-84907308958&doi=10.3141%2F2317-02&partnerID=40&md5=1a47ea09b043fc4a44705e82336b293a","EMBARQ, World Resources Institute, Center for Sustainable Transport, 10 G Street, NE, Suite 800, Washington, 20002, DC, United States; EMBARQ Brasil, Rua Luciana de Abreu 471/801, Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, 90570-060, Brazil; Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Rice University, MS-519, 6100 Main Street, Houston, 77005, TX, United States","Duduta N., EMBARQ, World Resources Institute, Center for Sustainable Transport, 10 G Street, NE, Suite 800, Washington, 20002, DC, United States; Adriazola C., EMBARQ, World Resources Institute, Center for Sustainable Transport, 10 G Street, NE, Suite 800, Washington, 20002, DC, United States; Hidalgo D., EMBARQ, World Resources Institute, Center for Sustainable Transport, 10 G Street, NE, Suite 800, Washington, 20002, DC, United States; Lindau L.A., EMBARQ Brasil, Rua Luciana de Abreu 471/801, Porto Alegre, Rio Grande do Sul, 90570-060, Brazil; Jaffe R., Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Rice University, MS-519, 6100 Main Street, Houston, 77005, TX, United States","The design choices made in the planning of a new bus rapid transit (BRT) or busway corridor (e.g., use of a center-lane or curbside configuration, counterflow lanes, and open or closed stations) affect not only the operational performance of the system but also the risks of crashes, injuries, and fatalities on the facility over its lifetime. With data from nine BRT systems and busways around the world (including Bogotá, Colombia; Curitiba, Brazil; Mexico City, Mexico; and Delhi, India), some of the road safety impacts of major BRT–busway corridor design characteristics are illustrated. The approach included a combination of crash frequency modeling, road safety inspections, and interviews with transit agency staff and safety experts. Center-lane systems tended generally to be safer than were curbside systems, and counterflow lanes were the most dangerous possible configuration. Some of the features that provide higher passenger capacity (such as multiple bus lanes and multiple docking bays at stations) may introduce new types of conflicts and crashes. In the planning of any bus system, trade-offs often need to be made between capacity, safety, and pedestrian accessibility along the corridor. This study provides the necessary elements for successfully integrating road safety considerations into the design and operation of future BRT systems and busways.","","Bus transportation; Buses; Economic and social effects; Pedestrian safety; Rapid transit; A-center; Bus Rapid Transit; Bus rapid transit systems; Bus way; Counterflow; Design features; High-performance bus; Operational performance; Road safety; Safety impact; Roads and streets","N. Duduta; EMBARQ, World Resources Institute, Center for Sustainable Transport, Washington, 10 G Street, NE, Suite 800, 20002, United States; email: nduduta@wri.org","","National Research Council","03611981","","TRRED","","English","Transp Res Rec","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-84907308958"
"Wibowo T.H.R.; Zumelzu A.","Wibowo, Try Haristyo R. (57679442000); Zumelzu, Antonio (57056274100)","57679442000; 57056274100","Urban shape and pedestrian traffic in southern Chile. The Valdivia case study; [Forma urbana y peatonalidad en el sur de Chile. Estudio de caso de Valdivia]","2021","AUS","","29","","96","103","0","10.4206/AUS.2021.N29-12","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85129851649&doi=10.4206%2FAUS.2021.N29-12&partnerID=40&md5=2f0b0bf882c949388f81d2ad6800d888","Spatial Planner, The Ministry of Agrarian Affairs and Spatial Planning, Indonesia; Master in Regional Development Planning and Management, Faculty of Spatial Planning, TU, Dortmund University, Germany; Arquitecto, Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Facultad de Arquitectura y Artes, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile; Doctor (Ph.D) en Planificación Sostenible de la Universidad Tecnológica de Eindhoven, Holanda. Académico del Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Facultad de Arquitectura y Artes, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile","Wibowo T.H.R., Spatial Planner, The Ministry of Agrarian Affairs and Spatial Planning, Indonesia, Master in Regional Development Planning and Management, Faculty of Spatial Planning, TU, Dortmund University, Germany; Zumelzu A., Arquitecto, Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Facultad de Arquitectura y Artes, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile, Doctor (Ph.D) en Planificación Sostenible de la Universidad Tecnológica de Eindhoven, Holanda. Académico del Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Facultad de Arquitectura y Artes, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile","There is a growing demand for pedestrian traffic in middle-sized cities to counteract the increasing use of the automobile. In Valdivia, vehicle dependence is mainly due to the expansion of urban soil to peripheries, increasing distances and complicating access to everyday needs. The article explores elements of urban form that impact on pedestrian traffic and discusses two neighborhoods in the city of Valdivia, Chile. The methods used include a quantitative analysis to measure the accessibility and scale of the built surroundings; and a qualitative analysis to assess spatial quality and route selection. The outcomes show no lineal relationship between pedestrian accessibility and block size, suggesting that the distance that a person is willing to walk depends on the purpose: transportation or recreation. Finally, this study makes recommendations to improve local planning in order to guide urban development towards a human scale. © 2021","barrio; Forma urbana; neighborhood; peatonalidad; pedestrian traffic; Urban shape; Valdivia; Valdivia","","T.H.R. Wibowo; Spatial Planner, The Ministry of Agrarian Affairs and Spatial Planning, Indonesia; email: haristyo.try@gmail.com","","Universidad Austral de Chile","0718204X","","","","English","Aus","Article","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85129851649"
"da Silva O.H.; Pitilin T.R.; Gobbo C.A.R.; Caxambu M.G.; Sanches S.D.P.; Neto G.D.A.","da Silva, Otavio Henrique (57208248493); Pitilin, Taiany Richard (57214912029); Gobbo, Caio Augusto Rabello (57214916776); Caxambu, Marcelo Galeazzi (55188766700); Sanches, Suely da Penha (6603470564); Neto, Generoso De Angelis (54398456200)","57208248493; 57214912029; 57214916776; 55188766700; 6603470564; 54398456200","Accessibility index for urban walkable spaces","2020","Acta Scientiarum - Technology","42","1","e45181","","","5","10.4025/actascitechnol.v42i1.45181","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85079507290&doi=10.4025%2Factascitechnol.v42i1.45181&partnerID=40&md5=28e1edae2cbfd9425c456b374a076225","Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, São Carlos, 13565-905, São Paulo, Brazil; Universidade Tecnológica Federal do Paraná, Campo Mourão, Paraná, Brazil; Universidade Estadual de Maringá, Maringá, Paraná, Brazil","da Silva O.H., Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, São Carlos, 13565-905, São Paulo, Brazil; Pitilin T.R., Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, São Carlos, 13565-905, São Paulo, Brazil; Gobbo C.A.R., Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, São Carlos, 13565-905, São Paulo, Brazil; Caxambu M.G., Universidade Tecnológica Federal do Paraná, Campo Mourão, Paraná, Brazil; Sanches S.D.P., Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, São Carlos, 13565-905, São Paulo, Brazil; Neto G.D.A., Universidade Estadual de Maringá, Maringá, Paraná, Brazil","Considering the importance of technical accessibility parameters to the adequacy of urban areas for all people, this study aimed to develop a quantification method of pedestrian accessibility based on the technical standardization. The Accessibility of Walkable Spaces index (AWS) is composed of seven measurable indicators according to standards of accessibility, ranging from 0 (Inaccessibility) to 1 (Accessibility). After an audit of 570 sidewalk stretches in São Tomé, State of Paraná, Brazil, the Inaccessible situation was verified as the most recurrent (60.3% of the sidewalk stretches). The best conditions were found in the more consolidated urban central area, as demonstrated by the KruskalWallis and Dunn tests (p < 0.05). The method showed adequate applicability. So, municipalities can use AWS index as a useful planning tool to prioritize interventions and provide inclusive and more sustainable environments to its citizens. © 2020, Eduem - Editora da Universidade Estadual de Maringa. All rights reserved.","Non-motorized transport; Social inclusion; Standardization; Sustainable mobility; Urban planning; Walkability","","O.H. da Silva; Departamento de Engenharia Civil, Universidade Federal de São Carlos, São Carlos, Rodovia Washington Luís, km 235, 13565-905, Brazil; email: silva.oh@outlook.com","","Eduem - Editora da Universidade Estadual de Maringa","18062563","","","","English","Acta Sci. Technol","Article","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access; Green Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85079507290"
"Marques F.","Marques, Franciele (58940149100)","58940149100","Pathways to Sustainability: An Overview of Active Mobility in Brazil","2026","Advances in Science, Technology and Innovation","","","","245","251","0","10.1007/978-3-031-99036-6_21","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-105031864503&doi=10.1007%2F978-3-031-99036-6_21&partnerID=40&md5=1d7906f861ef8c832849651f6f44d4b4","University of Debrecen, Debrecen, Hungary","Marques F., University of Debrecen, Debrecen, Hungary","This article presents an overview of active mobility in Brazil, examining how it is influenced by urban planning, socio-cultural and economic aspects, government policies, safety, and accessibility. The analysis aims to investigate the impact of urban planning and infrastructure development on active mobility patterns in Brazilian cities. It explores how social and cultural factors, intertwined with economic considerations, shape the choices individuals make in adopting active modes of transportation. Government policies and initiatives are also analyzed for their effectiveness, and the role of safety perception and accessibility in influencing transportation choices is assessed, as well as the health and environmental aspects of active mobility, shedding light on its contributions to public health and sustainable living. Based on the literature review and statistical data, this article aims to provide a nuanced understanding of the factors influencing active mobility in Brazil and contribute to ongoing academic discussions on urban planning, public health, and environmental sustainability, offering valuable insights for policymakers, researchers, and practitioners alike. © The Author(s), under exclusive license to Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2026.","Active mobility; Sustainable mobility; Urban mobility policy; Urban planning; Walkability","","F. Marques; University of Debrecen, Debrecen, Hungary; email: franmarques@mailbox.unideb.hu","Mahmoud I.H.; Bibri S.E.","Springer Nature","25228714","978-303199035-9","","","English","Adv. Sci. Tech. Inno.","Conference paper","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-105031864503"
"Sagaris L.; Berríos E.; Tiznado-Aitken I.","Sagaris, Lake (36549089500); Berríos, Emilio (50160975100); Tiznado-Aitken, Ignacio (57194448198)","36549089500; 50160975100; 57194448198","Using PAR to frame sustainable transport and social justice on policy agendas. A pilot experience in two contrasting Chilean cities","2020","Journal of Transport Geography","83","","102654","","","24","10.1016/j.jtrangeo.2020.102654","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85078997815&doi=10.1016%2Fj.jtrangeo.2020.102654&partnerID=40&md5=684749ad0fa7ec64ece723159855b5de","Department of Transport Engineering and Logistics, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Vicuña Mackenna, 4860, Santiago, Chile; Center for Sustainable Urban Development (CEDEUS), Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile","Sagaris L., Department of Transport Engineering and Logistics, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Vicuña Mackenna, 4860, Santiago, Chile; Berríos E., Center for Sustainable Urban Development (CEDEUS), Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Santiago, Chile; Tiznado-Aitken I., Department of Transport Engineering and Logistics, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Vicuña Mackenna, 4860, Santiago, Chile","If sustainable transport is defined by emissions and energy, urban passenger transport in Chile could be considered “sustainable”, with two-thirds of trips made by walking, cycling or public transit. Recent studies, however, reveal that gender and equity issues are highly problematic, pointing to tensions between environmental and social sustainability. Given these tensions, a university-community collaboration, the Laboratory for Social Change, developed a pilot methodology to define and evaluate Transport Justice. We sought a relatively simple instrument, a Transport Justice report (Balance de Transporte Justo, BTJ) that could combine experiential and academic knowledge and thereby influence policy and decision-making more effectively. We used a participatory action research (PAR) approach to bring together community leaders and university researchers, and consider experiential and research data, through this “transport justice” lens. To start, we introduced the idea of “transport justice” with researchers in different disciplines and citizen organizations involved in relatively specific battles: fighting a highway, for better cycling facilities, or for reduced road speeds, for example. We focused on established issues, such as universal access, walkability, cycle-inclusion, but added children's freedom and autonomy, the wise city (older adults, heritage, identity), care and land use, and transport impacts on ecological services. Building on this collaboration, we also applied a transport justice survey in two contrasting Chilean cities, Santiago and Temuco. Our analysis reveals that, despite a planning system that favours high-income households whose members rely mainly on cars, the majority of pedestrians, cyclists, public transit and even car users would prefer a redistribution of road space and investment in favour of active transport. During the next phase of research (2020–2021), we will test how well these results are taken up by citizen organizations, politicians and senior government staff from all parties. This will allow us to evaluate its effectiveness as a policy and power distributing instrument. © 2020 Elsevier Ltd","Cycle-inclusion; Developing countries; Gender; PAR; Sustainability; Transport justice; Walkability","Araucania; Chile; Metropolitana; Temuco; action research; decision making; developing world; ecosystem service; gender issue; participatory approach; social justice; sustainability; transportation policy; walking","L. Sagaris; Department of Transport Engineering and Logistics, Pontificia Universidad Católica de Chile, Vicuña Mackenna, 4860, Chile; email: lsagaris@uc.cl","","Elsevier Ltd","09666923","","","","English","J. Transp. Geogr.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85078997815"
"Zumelzu A.; Espinoza D.","Zumelzu, Antonio (57056274100); Espinoza, Daniel (55255495900)","57056274100; 55255495900","Development of a methodology to evaluate sustainability in neighbourhoods of intermediate cities in Chile; [Elaboración de una metodología para evaluar sostenibilidad en barrios de ciudades intermedias en Chile]","2019","Revista 180","44","","","80","94","18","10.32995/rev180.Num-44.(2019).art-474","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85079391564&doi=10.32995%2Frev180.Num-44.%282019%29.art-474&partnerID=40&md5=0ec2cb3c0cb9c1689e2eb4b039a26b95","Universidad Austral, Valdivia, Chile; Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile","Zumelzu A., Universidad Austral, Valdivia, Chile; Espinoza D., Universidad de Chile, Santiago, Chile","Urban studies related to sustainability are undergoing a phase of rich experimentation, with the exploration of different methodologies which aim to deal with current and future impacts of climate change in cities. This involves new challenges for the redevelopment of urban areas. Such challenges are especially relevant in times when major urban transformations are occurring in the global south. This article aims to elaborate a methodology to explore and evaluate the sustainable potential of the urban form in neighbourhoods of intermediate scale cities. The methodology addresses six criteria related with sustainability of the built environment: scale, accessibility, diversity, connectivity, density and nodality. This methodology is applied in a neighbourhood in the city of Temuco in southern Chile. The results show the importance of building adaptability to generate diversity of uses, which in turn promotes greater sustainability of the urban form. On the other hand, the over-density of population and housing in residential lots decreases pedestrian accessibility in the interior streets, while vertically mixed use and the variation of densities in urban blocks continues to be the best response to promote social interaction and high collective activity in the urban space. The article concludes on the operational value of the methodology and reflects upon future advances to promote the development of more sustainable urban forms in the intermediate cities of southern Chile. © 2019 Universidad Diego Portales. All rights reserved.","Built environment; Intermediate-sized cities; Sustainability; Urban morphology","","","","Universidad Diego Portales","07182309","","","","Spanish","Rev. 180","Article","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85079391564"
"Gomez L.F.; Soto-Salazar C.; Guerrero J.; Garcia M.; Parra D.C.","Gomez, Luis F. (34770598300); Soto-Salazar, Carolina (57216941202); Guerrero, José (57217672798); Garcia, María (57204121613); Parra, Diana C. (55760782500)","34770598300; 57216941202; 57217672798; 57204121613; 55760782500","Neighborhood environment, self-rated health and quality of life in Latin America","2021","Health Promotion International","35","2","","196","204","24","10.1093/HEAPRO/DAY117","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85085455869&doi=10.1093%2FHEAPRO%2FDAY117&partnerID=40&md5=59354248b592d03f73db0981b7730bb7","Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; Program in Physical Therapy, School of Medicine, Washington University in St. Louis, St. Louis, MO, United States","Gomez L.F., Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; Soto-Salazar C., Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; Guerrero J., Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; Garcia M., Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; Parra D.C., Program in Physical Therapy, School of Medicine, Washington University in St. Louis, St. Louis, MO, United States","To conduct a systematic review examining the associations between neighborhood environments and self-rated health (SRH) and health-related quality of life (HR-QOL) in the urban context of Latin America. We conducted a structured search of quantitative studies in three bibliographic databases published in Spanish, English, Portuguese and French from January 1990 to December 2015. We restricted the search to studies conducted in Latin-American cities with one million and more inhabitants. Eleven studies were finally included in the analysis. Ten were cross-sectional studies and one was a cohort follow-up study. Two studies found positive associations between accessibility to parks and HR-QOL. One study found that high neighborhood social capital was positively associated with SRH. Neighborhood socioeconomic status was positively associated with both HR-QOL and SRH in two studies. A walkable neighborhood was positively associated with SRH in two studies. Three studies included attributes related with neighborhood security perception and road safety, with higher scores of HR-QOL, both in the physical and mental dimensions, while high levels of street noise were negatively associated. Narrowness and slope of streets were negatively associated with SRH. No association was found between the perception of neighborhood security and SRH. The results of this systematic review show that several studies conducted in Latin America have found significant associations between neighborhood environment and SRH and HRQOL. However, the relatively small number of studies and the heterogeneity among them require further studies to better understand this topic in the region. © The Author(s) 2019","Health-related quality of life; Self-rated health; Social capital; Urban environment; Urban health","Diagnostic Self Evaluation; Environment Design; Humans; Latin America; Quality of Life; Residence Characteristics; demography; environmental planning; human; psychology; quality of life; self evaluation; South and Central America","L.F. Gomez; Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Social, Facultad de Medicina, Pontificia Universidad Javeriana, Bogotá, Colombia; email: l.gomezg@javeriana.edu.co","","Oxford University Press","09574824","","HPINE","30753541","English","Health Promot. Int.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85085455869"
"Gonzalez-Urango H.; Inturri G.; Le Pira M.; García-Melón M.","Gonzalez-Urango, Hannia (57194062509); Inturri, Giuseppe (14054058500); Le Pira, Michela (56780165600); García-Melón, Mónica (21740845600)","57194062509; 14054058500; 56780165600; 21740845600","Planning for Pedestrians with a Participatory Multicriteria Approach","2020","Journal of Urban Planning and Development","146","3","05020007","","","28","10.1061/(ASCE)UP.1943-5444.0000585","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85083442068&doi=10.1061%2F%28ASCE%29UP.1943-5444.0000585&partnerID=40&md5=baf2828b7fc5d24faf7a6d84d99f2c10","Ingenio (CSIC-UPV), Universitat Politècnica de València, Ciudad Politécnica de la Innovación, Edif 8E 4°, Camino de Vera s/n, Valencia, 46022, Spain; Universidad Simón Bolívar, Facultad de Ingenierías, Barranquilla, Colombia; Dept. of Electric, Electronic and Computer Engineering, Univ. of Catania, Via Santa Sofia 64, Catania, 95125, Italy; Dept. of Civil Engineering and Architecture, Univ. of Catania, Via Santa Sofia 64, Catania, 95125, Italy","Gonzalez-Urango H., Ingenio (CSIC-UPV), Universitat Politècnica de València, Ciudad Politécnica de la Innovación, Edif 8E 4°, Camino de Vera s/n, Valencia, 46022, Spain, Universidad Simón Bolívar, Facultad de Ingenierías, Barranquilla, Colombia; Inturri G., Dept. of Electric, Electronic and Computer Engineering, Univ. of Catania, Via Santa Sofia 64, Catania, 95125, Italy; Le Pira M., Dept. of Civil Engineering and Architecture, Univ. of Catania, Via Santa Sofia 64, Catania, 95125, Italy; García-Melón M., Ingenio (CSIC-UPV), Universitat Politècnica de València, Ciudad Politécnica de la Innovación, Edif 8E 4°, Camino de Vera s/n, Valencia, 46022, Spain","The design of accessible walking routes needs to take into account the different stakeholders' preferences and factors affecting walking. It is a complex issue which policy-makers should deal with to foster sustainable mobility. A participatory multicriteria decision analysis approach is presented to help the planning and designing of pedestrian routes, based on a sound analysis of factors affecting walking behavior and the attributes of the roads, and a stakeholder-driven evaluation of the same. A group of different stakeholders has been involved to select the criteria for designing pedestrian routes in the city center of Cartagena (Colombia). Some of them have been selected based on the results of a social network analysis (SNA) to be involved as key stakeholders for the evaluation of the selected criteria through an analytic network process (ANP). An index to measure the importance of each criterion in designing pedestrian routes has been obtained. Results provide valuable inputs to understand how to redesign and reconfigure streets for pedestrians in a city so as to improve walkability and foster a shift toward active and sustainable transport modes. © 2020 American Society of Civil Engineers.","Analytic network process; Pedestrian accessibility; Pedestrian mobility; Pedestrian route design; Stakeholder analysis; Urban walkability","Bolivar [Colombia]; Cartagena [Bolivar]; Colombia; Decision theory; Analytic network process; Multi-criteria approach; Multi-criteria decision analysis; Pedestrian routes; Planning and designings; Sustainable mobility; Sustainable transport; Walking behavior; accessibility; multicriteria analysis; participatory approach; pedestrian; policy making; social network; stakeholder; urban planning; walking; Decision making","H. Gonzalez-Urango; Ingenio (CSIC-UPV), Universitat Politècnica de València, Ciudad Politécnica de la Innovación, Valencia, Edif 8E 4°, Camino de Vera s/n, 46022, Spain; email: gonzalezurango@gmail.com","","American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE)","07339488","","","","English","J. Urban Plann. Dev.","Article","Final","All Open Access; Green Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85083442068"
"Chavez-Rodriguez L.; Lomas R.T.; Curry L.","Chavez-Rodriguez, Libertad (57219355291); Lomas, Raquel Treviño (57219360284); Curry, Laura (57219360551)","57219355291; 57219360284; 57219360551","Environmental justice at the intersection: Exclusion patterns in urban mobility narratives and decision making in Monterrey, Mexico","2020","Die Erde","151","2-3","","116","128","10","10.12854/erde-2020-479","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85092368038&doi=10.12854%2Ferde-2020-479&partnerID=40&md5=a900c5b1ed635be305ad746f486d3034","CIESAS and CONACYT, Morelos Ote. 822 Centro, Monterrey, Nuevo León, Mexico; Diego de Montemayor Nte. 355 Centro, Monterrey, Nuevo León, Mexico; University of Buffalo, 20 NW 16th Ave. #215, Portland, 97209, OR, United States","Chavez-Rodriguez L., CIESAS and CONACYT, Morelos Ote. 822 Centro, Monterrey, Nuevo León, Mexico; Lomas R.T., Diego de Montemayor Nte. 355 Centro, Monterrey, Nuevo León, Mexico; Curry L., University of Buffalo, 20 NW 16th Ave. #215, Portland, 97209, OR, United States","Placing the urban environment of Monterrey, Mexico at the center of our research, this paper examines how urban mobility intersects with gender and environmental justice. As a transdisciplinary team of scholars, artists, and activists, we examine the urban mobility discourses and discuss how transportation and urban narratives such as sustainable mobility and human cities reinforce: a) a car centered dominant narrative that maintains environmental and mobility injustices, and b) the socio-spatial segregation, exclusion, and accelerated gentrification processes in Monterrey. And, we discuss how these narratives exclude queer and feminist perspectives and their bodies. Using official and media reports we look at how the political and economic elites use narratives to prop up an imaginary of urban equality as part of a walkable and/or cycling city. These narratives maintain a status quo that includes new housing and transportation construction as part of an ongoing unjust system that we refer to as intersectional, in regards to gender, racism, socio-economic status, and age. We conclude environmental justice can only be achieved with mobility justice and that to achieve mobility justice we need to queer the city. To queer a city is when mobility patterns and connectivity of neighborhoods in the periphery are prioritized; when transparency mechanisms, gender perspectives and embodied experiences are the norm, and when aspiration includes achieving a less polluted, sustainable and equitable city. © 2020 Gesellschaft fur Erdkunde zu Berlin. All rights reserved.","Critical discourse analysis; Intersectionality; Socio-spatial segregation; Transit deserts; Urban mobility","Mexico [North America]; Monterrey; Nuevo Leon; decision making; environmental justice; gentrification; interdisciplinary approach; residential development; residential mobility; transportation infrastructure; urban area; urban planning","L. Chavez-Rodriguez; CIESAS and CONACYT, Monterrey, Morelos Ote. 822 Centro, Mexico; email: libertadchavez@ciesas.edu.mx","","Gesellschaft fur Erdkunde zu Berlin","00139998","","","","English","Erde","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85092368038"
"Da Silva M.B.C.; Bebber S.; Fachinelli A.C.; De Atayde Moschen S.; De Lucena Perini R.","Da Silva, Marcelo Benetti Correa (57218372147); Bebber, Suélen (56703505600); Fachinelli, Ana Cristina (54789528400); De Atayde Moschen, Suane (57209241397); De Lucena Perini, Rafael (57215054271)","57218372147; 56703505600; 54789528400; 57209241397; 57215054271","City life satisfaction: A measurement for smart and sustainable cities from the citizens' perspective","2019","International Journal of Knowledge-Based Development","10","4","","338","383","15","10.1504/IJKBD.2019.105126","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85079807316&doi=10.1504%2FIJKBD.2019.105126&partnerID=40&md5=d7a7f573be76912cbfe940de50910301","Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil","Da Silva M.B.C., Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil; Bebber S., Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil; Fachinelli A.C., Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil; De Atayde Moschen S., Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil; De Lucena Perini R., Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, Caxias do Sul, 95070-560, Brazil","The study aims to contribute to the current panorama of instruments that qualify cities by presenting an approach of sustainable goals and indicators. Insight from inhabitants about their cities reveal dimensions and attributes not captured by official indicators. The focus of this study is to define appropriate indicators for sustainability and smartness of cities according to their citizens, considering the idiosyncrasies of local contexts and less notable dimensions pointed out in earlier studies. The scale is based on consolidated metrics, such as the UN Sustainable Development Goals, and the ISO 37120/2017, in association with the European Barometer and American Barometer. The CITYLIFESAT (City Life Satisfaction) scale was tested and validated in Southern Brazil through exploratory and confirmatory factor analysis, and discriminant analysis. The results show that citizens' satisfaction is primarily linked to health and safety, well-being, recreation, public transport, walkability, social inclusion and participation, primary services, city attachment, and environment. © 2019 Inderscience Enterprises Ltd.","American barometer; Citizen perception; Citizens' satisfaction; European barometer; NBR ISO 37120; Perceived residential environment quality indicators; PREQI; Quality of life; SDGs; Sense of community; Sustainable development goals; Urban development","Barometers; Discriminant analysis; Factor analysis; Houses; Planning; Urban growth; Citizens' satisfaction; NBR ISO 37120; PREQI; Quality of life; Residential environment; SDGs; Sense of community; Urban development; Sustainable development","S. Bebber; Graduate Program in Business Administration, Universidade de Caxias Do sul, Caxias do Sul, 1130 Francisco Getúlio Vargas, 95070-560, Brazil; email: bebber.suelen@gmail.com","","Inderscience Publishers","20404468","","","","English","Int. J. Knowl. Based Dev.","Review","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85079807316"
"Zumelzu A.; Estrada M.; Jara C.; Pea C.","Zumelzu, A. (57056274100); Estrada, M. (57926945500); Jara, C. (58959560200); Pea, C. (57217523508)","57056274100; 57926945500; 58959560200; 57217523508","Effects of the Built Environment on Pedestrian Accessibility in Neighbourhoods in Southern Chile. the case of Temuco, Chile","2020","IOP Conference Series: Earth and Environmental Science","503","1","012093","","","3","10.1088/1755-1315/503/1/012093","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85087340585&doi=10.1088%2F1755-1315%2F503%2F1%2F012093&partnerID=40&md5=de62993680095b8508457e02417a0f64","Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile; Escuela de Arquitectura, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile","Zumelzu A., Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile; Estrada M., Instituto de Arquitectura y Urbanismo, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile; Jara C., Escuela de Arquitectura, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile; Pea C., Escuela de Arquitectura, Universidad Austral de Chile, Chile","The aim of this article is to evaluate the effects of the built environment on pedestrian accessibility in two neighborhoods in the area of Alemania Avenue, in the city of Temuco, Chile. The methodology integrates three evaluation methods: the method Morpho to explore the morphological conditions that influence walkability; The method developed by Emily Talen to measure walking distance to local services and facilities; and People Following method from Space Syntax theory to evaluate which spatial factors influence the choice of routes and to explore the distance that people walk between their points of interests. Results show that the choice of routes that people take to reach a destination is not defined by the shortest route, but rather by the spatial quality of streets and street frontages. The study suggests that elements such as blind walls, the absence of green spaces and the decrease in the size of sidewalks on streets affects negatively in the choice of routes, and consequently pedestrian accessibility. The article concludes with recommendations for urban planning neighborhoods towards a more sustainable future. © 2020 Published under licence by IOP Publishing Ltd.","","Urban planning; Built environment; Evaluation methods; Green spaces; Local service; Points of interest; Space syntax theory; Spatial factors; Spatial quality; Sustainable development","","Rossel G.S.","Institute of Physics Publishing","17551307","","","","English","IOP Conf. Ser. Earth Environ. Sci.","Conference paper","Final","All Open Access; Gold Open Access","Scopus","2-s2.0-85087340585"
"Barrera-Fernández D.; Hernández-Escampa M.","Barrera-Fernández, Daniel (56940829600); Hernández-Escampa, Marco (33867564700)","56940829600; 33867564700","Mobility in urban events: walkability and accessibility in the Guelaguetza","2022","Annals of Leisure Research","25","2","","247","272","5","10.1080/11745398.2020.1800497","https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85089252006&doi=10.1080%2F11745398.2020.1800497&partnerID=40&md5=e20716145187841d9df324a1a0d6645f","Faculty of Architecture, Autonomous University of Oaxaca “Benito Juárez”, Oaxaca, Mexico","Barrera-Fernández D., Faculty of Architecture, Autonomous University of Oaxaca “Benito Juárez”, Oaxaca, Mexico; Hernández-Escampa M., Faculty of Architecture, Autonomous University of Oaxaca “Benito Juárez”, Oaxaca, Mexico","Walkability plays a key role in visitors’ satisfaction and experience of events hosted in historic centres. In addition, the lack of physical accessibility is one of the main environmental barriers to the participation of persons with reduced mobility in artistic and cultural events. The objective of the research is to analyse the existing walkability and accessibility measures in the Guelaguetza Festival (Oaxaca, Mexico). Mixed methods, especially qualitative, but also quantitative ones, were applied: direct observation of visitors moving along the streets of central Oaxaca, architectural analysis of the main venue, application of a questionnaire, interactions with attendees and officials, and analysis of public policy documents. The results showed relevant differences according to the visitor’s background and severe restrictions for persons with reduced mobility. However, they allowed suggesting some urban improvements to enhance attendees’ satisfaction with the festival. © 2020 Australia and New Zealand Association of Leisure Studies.","accessibility; active mobility; Event Experience Scale; tourist-historic city; touristification; Walkability","","D. Barrera-Fernández; Faculty of Architecture, Autonomous University of Oaxaca “Benito Juárez”, Oaxaca, Mexico; email: barrera.uabjo@gmail.com","","Routledge","11745398","","","","English","Ann. Leis Res.","Article","Final","","Scopus","2-s2.0-85089252006"
